  <!-- Main Content -->
  <main class="py-12">
    <section class="max-w-screen-xl mx-auto px-6">

      <!-- What is Insertion Sort -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">What is Insertion Sort?</h2>
        <p class="section-content">
          Insertion Sort is a simple sorting algorithm that builds the sorted array one element at a time. It works similarly to how we might sort playing cards in our hands.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- How Insertion Sort Works -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">How does Insertion Sort work?</h2>
        <ol class="section-content list-disc">
          <li><strong>Step 1:</strong> Start with the second element of the array (index 1). This is the element to be inserted into the sorted portion of the array.</li>
          <li><strong>Step 2:</strong> Compare the current element with the elements in the sorted portion of the array (to the left of it).</li>
          <li><strong>Step 3:</strong> Shift elements in the sorted portion that are greater than the current element to the right by one position.</li>
          <li><strong>Step 4:</strong> Insert the current element into the correct position in the sorted portion of the array.</li>
          <li><strong>Step 5:</strong> Repeat the process for the next element until the entire array is sorted.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- Time Complexity -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">Time Complexity of Insertion Sort</h2>
        <p class="section-content">
          The time complexity of Insertion Sort is as follows:
        </p>
        <ul class="section-content list-disc">
          <li><strong>Best case:</strong> O(n) - When the array is already sorted.</li>
          <li><strong>Average case:</strong> O(n^2) - When the array is randomly ordered.</li>
          <li><strong>Worst case:</strong> O(n^2) - When the array is sorted in reverse order.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- Advantages -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">Advantages of Insertion Sort</h2>
        <ul class="section-content list-disc">
          <li>Simple and easy to understand.</li>
          <li>Efficient for small datasets.</li>
          <li>In-place sorting algorithm (does not require additional memory).</li>
          <li>Stable sort (preserves the order of equal elements).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- Disadvantages -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">Disadvantages of Insertion Sort</h2>
        <ul class="section-content list-disc">
          <li>Not efficient for large datasets, with a time complexity of O(n^2) in the average and worst cases.</li>
          <li>Does not perform well with large or nearly unsorted arrays.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- Applications -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">Applications of Insertion Sort</h2>
        <ul class="section-content list-disc">
          <li>Used for small datasets or when the array is nearly sorted.</li>
          <li>Efficient when sorting a list with only a few elements out of order.</li>
          <li>Frequently used in online sorting where elements are inserted one by one.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- Example -->
      <div class="section-box">
        <h2 class="section-header">Insertion Sort Example</h2>
        <div class="section-content">
          <p>Consider the array: <code>[5, 3, 8, 4, 2]</code></p>
          <p>Step-by-step sorting:</p>
          <ul class="list-disc pl-6">
            <li>Pass 1: <code>[3, 5, 8, 4, 2]</code> (Insert 3 before 5)</li>
            <li>Pass 2: <code>[3, 5, 8, 4, 2]</code> (No change as 8 is in correct position)</li>
            <li>Pass 3: <code>[3, 4, 5, 8, 2]</code> (Insert 4 before 5)</li>
            <li>Pass 4: <code>[2, 3, 4, 5, 8]</code> (Insert 2 at the start)</li>
          </ul>
          <p>Final sorted array: <code>[2, 3, 4, 5, 8]</code></p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </section>
